        datacite:description   "The scheme represents figure 1 of the interim report of the consortium NFDI4BIOIMAGE submitted in February 2026. It summarizes key achievements and related metrics accomplished in the past three years linked to the corresponding central objectives listed in the application of the consortium. Key visions and concepts are further emphasized using illustrations and cropped elements thereof of Henning Falk, including 'Monolithic vs. chunked', 'Bea computes' and 'FAIR re-use' ©2022 NumFOCUS, as well as of the NFDI4BIOIMAGE 2026 wall calendar December page 'It's time to publish - where can bioimage data go? by Henning Falk' used under a CC BY 4.0 license. Modifications to the drawings include cropping.\n\nNFDI4BIOIMAGE is funded by Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft (DFG), grant number NFDI 46/1, project number 501864659.";
        datacite:resourceType  "Figure";
        datacite:right         "None" , "Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International";
        datacite:title         "Objectives and key achievements of NFDI4BIOIMAGE as of February 2026" .

<https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18957947>
        rdf:type               obo:T4FS_0000113;
        datacite:IsPartOf      <https://zenodo.org/communities/nfdi4bioimage/>;
        datacite:IsVersionOf   <https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18957946>;
        datacite:Issued        "2026-03-11"^^xs:date;
        datacite:Updated       "2026-03-11"^^xs:date;
        datacite:creator       orcid:0000-0003-2237-1147;
        datacite:description   "This short presentation provides a concise introduction to Data Management Plans (DMPs) in the context of and bioimaging. It explains what DMPs are, why they are important for research projects, and how they contribute to transparent, reproducible, and FAIR research practices.\n\nThe slides outline commonly used templates and tools that support researchers in creating and maintaining DMPs. In addition, the presentation highlights important considerations for bioimaging data, including file formats, metadata annotation, handling of large data sets and open software tools.\n\nDesigned as a brief educational resource, the presentation can be used for introductory teaching, workshops, or self-learning by researchers and students who are new to research data management and data management planning.\n\nWe acknowledge funding by the Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft (DFG, German Research Foundation) under the National Research Data Infrastructure – NFDI 46/1 – 501864659.";
        datacite:resourceType  "Diagram";
        datacite:right         "None" , "Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International";
        datacite:subject       "data management plans" , "research data management" , "bioimaging" , "nfdi4bioimage";
        datacite:title         "Easy creation of your Bioimage Data Management Plan" .

